rlm-git-squash-branch

Interactively squash every commit on the current branch since the merge
base with the target branch into a single signed-off commit, prompting
for confirmation before each destructive step.

The target branch is the base branch of the current PR (resolved via
`gh pr view --json baseRefName`) if one exists, otherwise origin's
default branch (`git symbolic-ref --short refs/remotes/origin/HEAD`,
with `git remote show origin` as fallback). The target is always
referenced as `origin/<branch>`.

Before any work, the current HEAD sha is recorded and a backup ref is
created at:

    refs/rlm-git-squash-branch/<branch>/<YYYYmmdd-HHMMSS>

This ref, together with the saved sha, is printed up front along with
the exact one-liner to revert the squash if anything goes wrong. The
backup ref is created only after the initial confirmation, but before
the fetch — so even a Ctrl-C mid-workflow leaves a trail back. (Note:
the working tree is also protected by the standard git reflog for
`<branch>`, which the recovery command falls back on naturally.)

Interactive steps (each prompts y/N — anything other than y|yes
aborts, leaving the branch in its current state):

  1. `git fetch --all` so the target reflects what's on the remote now.
  2. `git reset <target>` (mixed) — moves HEAD to the target branch tip
     and leaves the diff in the working tree. Before prompting, prints
     the merge base, target sha, commit count, and the list of commits
     that will be collapsed.
  3. `git add -A` to stage everything.
  4. `git commit -s -e -F -` with the saved squash message piped in as
     the initial editor buffer. Close the editor with an empty buffer
     to abort the commit (recovery instructions print regardless).

Refuses to run when:
  - HEAD is detached,
  - the working tree is dirty,
  - the current branch is the target branch itself,
  - HEAD is already at the target tip (nothing to squash),
  - reset leaves no staged changes (nothing to squash).

If any step is declined or fails, prints the recovery one-liner:

    git reset --hard <original_sha> && git update-ref -d <backup_ref>

After a successful commit, also prints the publish commands:

    git push --force-with-lease

  (or, when the remote branch doesn't yet exist:)

    git push -u origin <current-branch>

`--force-with-lease` is used rather than `--force` so the push aborts
if someone else pushed to the same branch in the meantime.

REQUIRES
  git
  gh (optional — only used to detect a PR base branch)
